WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.380
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger. Last time in&nbsp;
this series on foundational issues in mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:23.310
we exposed a really major problem with the notion&nbsp;
of function in its use in modern mathematics. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.310 --> 00:00:29.400
are going to have to rethink how we think about&nbsp;
functions, and today I want to talk a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:36.300
philosophically or meta-mathematically about&nbsp;
the right orientation to have towards not just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:41.400
functions but also towards mathematics in&nbsp;
general. This is an issue that's going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:48.360
touch on different issues within mathematics.&nbsp;
I'd like to frame the discussion in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:56.490
a dichotomy between closed concepts and open&nbsp;
concepts. I want to explain what I mean by that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.490 --> 00:01:03.210
and the guiding idea for us today is that&nbsp;
mathematics itself is an open system.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:11.730
So, to introduce this idea of this division&nbsp;
between things, let's talk about a kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.730 --> 00:01:19.740
physical or geographical analogy. So, here's&nbsp;
our planet Earth, an artist's representation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:28.770
Here's Australia, the equator, planet Earth, a&nbsp;
round sphere sitting inside space. And here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:35.970
an alternate kind of possible view of this&nbsp;
situation, where we also have Australia here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:44.970
but now imagined as part of a Flat Earth. Okay,&nbsp;
this is a non-existent world, but if you were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:52.890
a primitive person, say 200,000 years ago, and&nbsp;
you were placed in the middle of Australia, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.890 --> 00:02:00.090
you would not initially know whether you're in a&nbsp;
situation like this or in a situation like this.

00:02:00.090 --> 00:02:05.880
So, let's imagine that we went back in time,&nbsp;
and some primitive peoples were placed in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:12.000
middle of Australia, and we start exploring&nbsp;
our landscape. After a few generations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.630
we would start increasing the range of&nbsp;
our explorations, our range of familiar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.630 --> 00:02:25.870
territory. After some thousands of years,&nbsp;
perhaps we might eventually expand to realize&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.870 --> 00:02:31.810
that Australia was a continent; there were&nbsp;
oceans around. Then, thousands of years later,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:36.400
we would eventually come to the realization&nbsp;
that we were actually on a round planet and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:43.600
that the total amount of land and sea in this&nbsp;
picture was ultimately finite. It was contained;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:48.310
it was a closed system. In other words,&nbsp;
the world that we actually live in.

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:54.880
But another possible scenario is that we imagine&nbsp;
initially that we are sort of on a flat earth,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:03.070
and perhaps it might be that as we explore&nbsp;
further and further, this planar aspect of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:09.310
world we live in simply extends. So, I want you&nbsp;
to conduct a thought experiment: imagine yourself&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:15.760
in an alternate universe where planet Earth is&nbsp;
not a round sphere like this but rather a plane,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:23.200
a flat more or less plane that extends or&nbsp;
appears to extend in all directions. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:29.020
as we go outwards, we simply discover more and&nbsp;
more lands, more and more continents, more and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:37.900
more oceans. It'll be hard for us to determine&nbsp;
that this process extends infinitely because we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:44.680
don't have a bird's-eye view of the whole thing.&nbsp;
What we have is increasing diameters of knowledge,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:51.190
and no matter how far we extend our knowledge in&nbsp;
this generation, the possibility exists that in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.190 --> 00:03:56.620
the next generation, people will go further&nbsp;
and discover more about this kind of world.

00:03:56.620 --> 00:04:01.720
So, this is an imagined world in&nbsp;
which there are no boundaries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:07.240
in which there's at least a potential for&nbsp;
continued expansion, where we never have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:13.240
final understanding of the world in which we&nbsp;
live. Okay, so these two pictures are quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:20.650
different psychologically. We live in this kind&nbsp;
of world; it's finite, it's closed. We understand,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.650 --> 00:04:26.950
in theory, pretty well everything about it&nbsp;
geographically. In this picture, it's open,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:31.660
it's unbounded, it's infinite, or perhaps&nbsp;
potentially infinite. We're not really sure,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:35.710
and there's always the possibility&nbsp;
of increasing our understanding.

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:42.700
This distinction between closed and open is&nbsp;
a meta-mathematical idea. It's not actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:46.720
within mathematics itself, so we're not&nbsp;
being completely precise. But let's say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:52.300
that closed roughly means that it's finite,&nbsp;
or that it's bounded, that it's enclosing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:59.950
that it can potentially be fully understood. While&nbsp;
open suggests to us something that's infinite,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:06.460
something that's unbounded, keeps going,&nbsp;
you can't fence it in. With an open system,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:12.430
it's never possible to fully understand it;&nbsp;
our understanding is always partial. And again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:16.150
let me emphasize that, in my opinion,&nbsp;
mathematics is more like an open system.

00:05:17.890 --> 00:05:22.090
So, let's have a look at some of these key&nbsp;
examples: concepts of number, function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:27.250
and sequence. From my point of view, these&nbsp;
are concepts which are really meta-concepts;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:32.140
they are things that we impose on mathematics&nbsp;
from the outside. But from the inside,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:34.900
we have to treat them in a different way. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:42.460
I want to suggest that mathematical definitions&nbsp;
need to respect this open aspect of the subject.

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:48.970
So, for example, let's look at the idea of a&nbsp;
number. I claim that there's no such concept&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.970 --> 00:05:55.810
within mathematics proper. The idea of a&nbsp;
number as something that counts something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.810 --> 00:06:01.750
is a meta-mathematical idea. We can frame that in&nbsp;
the English language that surrounds mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:08.290
but it's very hard—in fact, I say impossible—to&nbsp;
define the notion of a general number within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.290 --> 00:06:15.250
mathematics itself. So, in the standard view, you&nbsp;
might be able to define what you mean by a number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:24.970
once and for all, and then different kinds of&nbsp;
numbers that you study are simply special cases&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.970 --> 00:06:31.210
of this more general definition that you've&nbsp;
already made. Another point of view, the open&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:37.120
point of view, is to think of number as not a&nbsp;
concept at all within mathematics. So, it's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:43.150
meta-mathematical concept. So, I put it in quotes,&nbsp;
and now what we do is we think of natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.150 --> 00:06:51.130
we think of defining objects called fractions,&nbsp;
integers, rational numbers. So, we think of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:59.530
concept of number in quotes as something that's&nbsp;
open, that keeps on going, there's no bound. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:04.210
we, for example, in our definitions may get to&nbsp;
a certain stage, but in the next generation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.210 --> 00:07:10.300
someone who's smarter, who thinks more about these&nbsp;
things, will be able to go further. But nobody&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:15.790
will ever get to the end of the notion of number;&nbsp;
there will always be a better way of thinking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:21.250
a more embracing way of thinking, a more&nbsp;
general way of thinking. The system is open.

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:27.280
Okay, this is a mental image that I want&nbsp;
you to have. It's not a precise thing;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:33.910
it's just an idea that mathematics is going&nbsp;
on beyond our view. So, we saw in our last&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:38.530
few videos that there are serious problems&nbsp;
with the notion of function, and here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.530 --> 00:07:43.240
my suggestion on how we should overcome that,&nbsp;
or how we should think about functions within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:49.750
mathematics. We should realize that there is no&nbsp;
such concept as a function, a general function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:55.120
within mathematics proper, but there are&nbsp;
many types of mathematical objects which act&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.120 --> 00:08:00.790
as functions. The usual idea is that it does&nbsp;
make sense to talk about what a function is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.790 --> 00:08:08.800
and then one simply inside this box of functions&nbsp;
carves out particular types of functions.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:15.310
Here is the preferred way of thinking about&nbsp;
things. We do not talk about a general function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:21.580
but rather what we do is we define different&nbsp;
kinds of objects which effectively are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.580 --> 00:08:26.320
specialized types of functions. So, we&nbsp;
can talk about—we haven't done this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:32.710
but eventually we will—we can talk about constant&nbsp;
functions, we can talk about linear functions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.710 --> 00:08:39.790
we can talk about continuous functions. We can&nbsp;
define these as types of mathematical objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.790 --> 00:08:47.290
which are very concretely specified. But there's&nbsp;
no limit to this notion; there will always be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.290 --> 00:08:58.700
further examples of functions, further extensions&nbsp;
of this basic idea. Again, an open system. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:05.780
it's a very important distinction between thinking&nbsp;
about a closed system and an open system, and most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:12.470
key concepts in mathematics are open. They're&nbsp;
like this notion of function. In particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.470 --> 00:09:15.890
the important idea of a sequence, which&nbsp;
we will also eventually talk about,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.890 --> 00:09:21.770
is exactly the same as like a number and&nbsp;
function. It also is an open concept.

00:09:21.770 --> 00:09:27.830
All right, so that's very good. Since&nbsp;
we're now on a sort of philosophical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.830 --> 00:09:32.780
or meta-mathematical trend here, next time&nbsp;
I'm going to continue and talk a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:38.210
about definitions and specifications and&nbsp;
the interpretation of definitions within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.210 --> 00:09:44.360
mathematics. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

